{
  "doc_id": "8792",
  "text": "Recently, mobility of sensor networks has attracted a lot of research interests due to its ability to decrease the overall energy consumption of the network. Animals were used as mobile sinks by Shah et al. [CITATION_1] to collect data from wild surroundings. Maximum Amount Shortest Path (MASP) [CITATION_2] was proposed to improve the network lifetime by optimizing the assignment of sensor nodes. In mobile element scheduling (MES) problem [CITATION_3] , a mobile element visits each sensor nodes individually to collect data from them. Weighted rendezvous planning (WRP) [CITATION_4] is proposed to find the near-optimal trajectory of a mobile sink. In [CITATION_5] , the mobile collector moves around the network and pauses at some anchor points such that it falls within the transmission range of all sensors and directly collects data from them. To balance energy consumption in the network, [CITATION_6] employed a mobile collector in the network. Mobility has been used in this work to overcome communication bottlenecks caused by spatial energy variation. An obstacle avoidance routing protocol with a mobile sink was proposed by Chanak et al. [CITATION_7] . In this work, the mobile sink finds the shortest path to collect data from the static sensors while avoiding the obstacles. In Mobile Collector Data Path Planning (MCPP) [CITATION_8] , many mobile collectors are employed to visit only certain sojourn points to collect data from the sensors in a single-hop.",
